      "side": 1,
      "message": "Our starting point is this expression:\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half3(fn(v), half2(123, 456)).yzzx;\n\nWhich optimizes to:\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half4(half2(123, 456).xyy, fn(v));\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half4(half3(123, 123, 456), fn(v));\n\nIn the previous implemention I expect that it was doing:\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half3(fn(v), half2(123, 456)).yzzx;\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half4(half2(123, 456).x, half2(123, 456).y, half2(123, 456).y, fn(v));\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half4(half(123), half(456), half(456), fn(v));\n    sk_FragColor \u003d half4(123, 456, 456, fn(v));\n\nGranted, it works out to a nice final representation, but it\u0027s further away from the starting expression and does a lot more cloning to get there. I think if flattening nested constructors is an optimization we care about, we would be better served to implement it as its own optimization. I don\u0027t have any idea if this would be beneficial.",
